@Sunny Agreed. Mine were very heavy, with an almost robbery exterior. They baked up quickly in the pans and I put them under a medium broiler. I just double checked all the quantities of the ingredients and the conversions to metric (I’m American in the UK). I even did it alongside the Bon Appetite video. And I’m an experienced baker. The batter rose but it never had the liquid consistency that Sam Yoo demonstrates in the video. Adding another cup of flour seemed like a lot and took it beyond a cake batter. I had to smooth out the batter in the pan with a spatula or it would’ve baked like a mountainous lump. (And I think I yielded only 3 inedible pancakes). 

There can be some confusion with American recipes because it’s never clear if one should use bicarbonate of soda or baking powder as the rising agent. Bicarbonate would be suitable for pancakes (and I make Marion Cunningham’s recipes all the time) whereas baking powder is more suitable for cakes and cookies. As these are pancakes, I went with bicarbonate but I never saw any bubbles. They came out like a not so distant relation to door stops. I think they needed baking powder, less flour and more buttermilk. The other components were all lovely so I’ll make some proper buttermilk pancakes tomorrow to use those up. 

Interested in any advice. Thanks!

