@MS you should form or cut your scones before chilling them (preferably in the freezer). This is not about resting the dough to form gluten, it’s about getting those fat globules in the cream cold again after mixing and forming the scones. The cold fat is what makes the scones tender and the freezing will inhibit gluten formation (and you can bake them from frozen). If you chill the dough prior to forming the scones you’ll risk warming the fat and overworking the mixture. 

Here’s a great blog from King Arthur that breaks down the cream v. butter when it comes to scones.

<a href="https://www.kingarthurbaking.com/blog/2019/03/19/cream-scones-vs-butter-scones" target="_blank">https://www.kingarthurbaking.com/blog/2019/03/19/cream-scones-vs-butter-scones</a>

